-- Brazilian Stock Movers: CCR, B2W and Usiminas Were Active
-- B y   D e n y s e   G o d o y
-- 2012-05-17T20:42:27Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-05-17/brazilian-stock-movers-gol-b2w-and-usiminas-are-active.html
The following companies had  unusual 
price changes in Sao Paulo trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the close. Preferred shares
are usually the most-traded class of stock.  The  Bovespa (IBOV)  Index slid 3.3 percent to 54,038.20.  CCR SA (CCRO3)  (CCRO3 BS) climbed 2.1 percent to 15.62 reais, the
biggest advance on the Bovespa. The toll-road operator reported
first-quarter net income that rose 65 percent to 288.6 million
reais ($143.5 million), according to a regulatory filing sent
late yesterday.  B2W Cia. Global de Varejo  (BTOW3 BS) fell 6.7 percent to
6.99 reais. Shares gained 16 percent yesterday as  Valor
Economico  reported  Lojas Americanas SA (LAME4)  will delist the online
retailer’s stock. B2W “doesn’t know of any reason” for the
recent fluctuations in its share price, according to a
regulatory filing sent late yesterday.  Voting shares of steelmaker  Usinas Siderurgicas de Minas
Gerais SA  (USIM3 BS) fell 7.1 percent to 13.29 reais, the lowest
since March 2009, after MSCI Inc. said yesterday it was removing
the stock from its Brazil index as of the close May 31. The
preferred stock (USIM5 BS) declined 5.4 percent to 9.51 reais.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Denyse Godoy in  Sao Paulo  at 
